# Four Principles of Writing Good Code

Context: [Frontend Fundamentals](https://frontend-fundamentals.com/code-quality/en/code/). Good frontend code is code that is **easy to change and ship**. Judge it with four lenses: **readability**, **predictability**, **cohesion**, and **coupling**. You rarely satisfy all four at once—prioritize based on the situation.

---

## 1. Readability

Can readers see at a glance what the code does? Reduce how much context they must hold at once, and let the code read naturally from top to bottom.

### 1.1 Separate code that doesn’t run together

**Rule**  
Do not keep branches that never execute at the same time (permissions, roles, etc.) tangled in a single function or component.

**Reasoning**  
When branches are interleaved, readers must track more context at once; mixed “blue path / red path” logic is hard to follow.

**Recommended Pattern**  
Keep a single top-level branch (`viewer ? A : B`) and move each path into its own component or function—for example `ViewerSubmitButton` / `AdminSubmitButton`—so each unit handles only one state.

```typescript
function SubmitButton() {
  const isViewer = useRole() === "viewer";

  return isViewer ? <ViewerSubmitButton /> : <AdminSubmitButton />;
}

function ViewerSubmitButton() {
  return <TextButton disabled>Submit</TextButton>;
}

function AdminSubmitButton() {
  useEffect(() => {
    showButtonAnimation();
  }, []);

  return <Button type="submit">Submit</Button>;
}
```

---

### 1.2 Abstract implementation details

**Rule**  
Hide implementation the reader must parse at once (hook arguments, intermediate state names, raw constants) behind intention-revealing names and boundaries (wrappers, HOCs).

**Reasoning**  
People can only hold a limited amount of information at once. Exposed implementation makes the core purpose of a screen like `LoginStartPage` hard to see.

**Recommended Pattern**

- Login guard: an `AuthGuard` wrapper or `withAuthGuard` HOC owns “if already logged in, redirect home”; the page focuses on login UI.
- Complex consent + overlay: colocate button, consent flow, and follow-up actions in something like `InviteButton`; the page only renders `InviteButton`.  
  Split abstractions so a reader tracks roughly six to seven chunks of context at a time.

```typescript
function App() {
  return (
    <AuthGuard>
      <LoginStartPage />
    </AuthGuard>
  );
}

function AuthGuard({ children }) {
  const status = useCheckLoginStatus();

  useEffect(() => {
    if (status === "LOGGED_IN") {
      location.href = "/home";
    }
  }, [status]);

  return status !== "LOGGED_IN" ? children : null;
}

function LoginStartPage() {
  /* ... logic for login ... */

  return <>{/* ... login related components ... */}</>;
}
```

---

### 1.3 Split by responsibility, not only by “type” of logic

**Rule**  
Avoid giant hooks or functions organized only by **shape** (“all query params”, “all APIs”). Split by **meaningful units** (per parameter, per feature).

**Reasoning**  
A hook like `usePageState()` that owns every URL param for a page can grow without bound and become long and hard to read. Any query change can also re-render every consumer of the hook.

**Recommended Pattern**  
Split into small hooks per query key, e.g. `useCardIdQueryParam()`. Names get clearer and the blast radius of edits shrinks.

```typescript
import { NumberParam, useQueryParam } from "use-query-params";

export function useCardIdQueryParam() {
  const [cardId, _setCardId] = useQueryParam("cardId", NumberParam);

  const setCardId = useCallback((cardId: number) => {
    _setCardId({ cardId }, "replaceIn");
  }, []);

  return [cardId ?? undefined, setCardId] as const;
}
```

---

### 1.4 Name complex conditions

**Rule**  
Give meaningful names—e.g. `isSameCategory`, `isPriceInRange`—to deeply nested conditions built from `filter`, `some`, and `&&`.

**Reasoning**  
Unnamed compound conditions force readers to track many things at once (working memory holds on the order of six items).

**Recommended Pattern**  
Use intermediate booleans or small steps so intent reads like prose (“same category and price in range”).  
For something as simple as `arr.map(x => x * 2)` used once, extra naming is usually unnecessary.

```typescript
const matchedProducts = products.filter((product) => {
  return product.categories.some((category) => {
    const isSameCategory = category.id === targetCategory.id;
    const isPriceInRange = product.prices.some(
      (price) => price >= minPrice && price <= maxPrice,
    );

    return isSameCategory && isPriceInRange;
  });
});
```

---

### 1.5 Name magic numbers (readability)

**Rule**  
Replace unexplained numeric or string literals with named constants.

**Reasoning**  
`delay(300)` alone does not say whether you wait for animation, server propagation, or leftover test code—collaborators may misunderstand and change it wrongly.

**Recommended Pattern**  
Name for context, e.g. `const ANIMATION_DELAY_MS = 300`, and call `delay(ANIMATION_DELAY_MS)`.

```typescript
const ANIMATION_DELAY_MS = 300;

async function onLikeClick() {
  await postLike(url);
  await delay(ANIMATION_DELAY_MS);
  await refetchPostLike();
}
```

---

### 1.6 Reduce context switching / eye movement

**Rule**  
Avoid layouts where understanding `policy.canInvite` requires jumping `policy.canInvite` → `getPolicyByRole` → `POLICY_SET` across the file. For simple permissions, keep the flow readable in one pass.

**Reasoning**  
More eye movement makes it harder to hold context and slows comprehension.

**Recommended Pattern**

- **A**: List role-specific UI with `switch (user.role)` from top to bottom.

```typescript
function Page() {
  const user = useUser();

  switch (user.role) {
    case "admin":
      return (
        <div>
          <Button disabled={false}>Invite</Button>
          <Button disabled={false}>View</Button>
        </div>
      );
    case "viewer":
      return (
        <div>
          <Button disabled={true}>Invite</Button>
          <Button disabled={false}>View</Button>
        </div>
      );
    default:
      return null;
  }
}
```

- **B**: Inline a glanceable object, e.g. `policy = { admin: {...}, viewer: {...} }[user.role]`.

```typescript
function Page() {
  const user = useUser();
  const policy = {
    admin: { canInvite: true, canView: true },
    viewer: { canInvite: false, canView: true }
  }[user.role];

  return (
    <div>
      <Button disabled={!policy.canInvite}>Invite</Button>
      <Button disabled={!policy.canView}>View</Button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

---

### 1.7 Simplify ternary operators

**Rule**  
Do not hide branching structure in nested ternaries; use `if` / `switch` or a sequence of `if` / `return` inside an IIFE.

**Reasoning**  
Nested ternaries make it hard to see which condition yields which value.

**Recommended Pattern**

```typescript
const status = (() => {
  if (ACondition && BCondition) return "BOTH";
  if (ACondition) return "A";
  if (BCondition) return "B";
  return "NONE";
})();
```

---

### 1.8 Make Comparisons Read from Left to Right

**Rule**
When writing range-checking conditions, always order the operands so they read naturally from left to right — smallest bound on the left, subject value in the middle, largest bound on the right. Avoid placing the subject value at the leftmost position when checking if it falls within a range.

**Reasoning**  
Human readers parse comparisons by naturally scanning left to right. When the subject value (e.g., `score`) appears on the left side of both comparisons — `score >= 80 && score <= 100` — the reader must mentally flip one of the operators and reconstruct the range. This increases cognitive load unnecessarily.

Ordering comparisons as `lowerBound <= value && value <= upperBound` mirrors the mathematical notation `lowerBound ≤ value ≤ upperBound`, which is the form most people already reason in. The intent of "value is between X and Y" becomes immediately visible without any mental transformation.

**Recommended Pattern**

```typescript
// ❌ Avoid — subject value appears first, forcing the reader to mentally reorder
if (a >= b && a <= c) { ... }
if (score >= 80 && score <= 100) { ... }
if (price >= minPrice && price <= maxPrice) { ... }

// ✅ Prefer — reads like a mathematical inequality from left to right
if (b <= a && a <= c) { ... }
if (80 <= score && score <= 100) { ... }
if (minPrice <= price && price <= maxPrice) { ... }
```

