### 2.3 Expose hidden logic

**Rule**  
A function's implementation must contain only the logic that its name, parameters, and return type imply. Extract any side effects (logging, analytics, navigation) and call them at the call site instead.

**Reasoning**  
When `fetchBalance()` silently logs an event, callers cannot predict the side effect from the function signature alone. Logging in unexpected places produces incorrect analytics, and errors in the side-effect logic can break the primary behavior.

**Recommended Pattern**

```typescript
// ❌ Avoid — logging is hidden inside a data-fetching function
async function fetchBalance(): Promise<number> {
  const balance = await http.get<number>("/balance");
  logging.log("balance_fetched"); // invisible to callers; may fire in wrong contexts
  return balance;
}

// ✅ Prefer — fetchBalance does exactly what its name says; logging lives at the call site
async function fetchBalance(): Promise<number> {
  return http.get<number>("/balance");
}

// Call site owns the side effect — intent is explicit
const handleUpdate = async () => {
  const balance = await fetchBalance();
  logging.log("balance_fetched"); // caller decides when/whether to log
  await syncBalance(balance);
};
```

