## 4. Coupling

When you change one place, where does impact spread? Keep impact predictable and bounded.

### 4.1 Manage responsibilities individually

**Rule**  
Avoid a single “all page query params” hook that many UI pieces and hooks depend on; Split responsibilities into focused, single-purpose units.

**Reasoning**  
A hook that manages every query parameter on a page becomes a dependency magnet. Every component that needs any query value will import it, silently coupling unrelated components together. One change ripples unpredictably across the entire page.

**Recommended Pattern**  
Split hooks per query parameter (same refactor as §1.3, motivated from a coupling angle).

```typescript
// ❌ Avoid — one hook owns everything; any change touches everything
export function usePageState() {
  const [query, setQuery] = useQueryParams({
    cardId: NumberParam,
    statementId: NumberParam,
    dateFrom: DateParam,
    dateTo: DateParam,
    statusList: ArrayParam,
  });
  // ... returns all values and setters as one blob
}

// ✅ Prefer — each query parameter is its own focused hook
import { useQueryParam, NumberParam } from "use-query-params";
import { useCallback } from "react";

export function useCardIdQueryParam() {
  const [cardId, _setCardId] = useQueryParam("cardId", NumberParam);

  const setCardId = useCallback((id: number) => {
    _setCardId(id, "replaceIn");
  }, []);

  return [cardId ?? undefined, setCardId] as const;
}

// Components only import the param they actually need — no accidental coupling
```

---

### 4.2 Allow duplicate code

**Rule**  
Do not extract a shared hook or component from surface similarity alone. If **logging, dismiss behavior, copy, or behavior may diverge per page**, duplication can be better.

**Reasoning**  
Shared abstractions can improve cohesion but raise coupling; more branches and options mean every caller must be retested on change.

**Recommended Pattern**  
Align with the team on whether log lines, bottom-sheet behavior, and UI will stay identical across pages long term. If not, keep per-page implementations.

```typescript
// ❌ Avoid — premature abstraction forces all pages to share behavior they may not want
export const useOpenMaintenanceBottomSheet = () => {
  const sheet = useMaintenanceBottomSheet();
  const logger = useLogger();

  return async (info: MaintenanceInfo) => {
    logger.log("Maintenance bottom sheet opened"); // what if PageA logs differently?
    const result = await sheet.open(info);
    if (result) logger.log("Maintenance bottom sheet notification clicked");
    closeView(); // what if PageB should NOT close after dismissal?
  };
};

// ✅ Prefer — each page owns its own copy; behavior can diverge independently
// PageA.tsx
const handleMaintenance = async (info: MaintenanceInfo) => {
  logger.log("maintenance_shown_page_a");
  const result = await maintenanceSheet.open(info);
  if (result) logger.log("maintenance_notification_clicked_page_a");
  closeView();
};

// PageB.tsx
const handleMaintenance = async (info: MaintenanceInfo) => {
  logger.log("maintenance_shown_page_b");
  await maintenanceSheet.open(info);
  // PageB intentionally does NOT close the view
};

// Consolidate into a shared hook only when behavior is confirmed identical and stable.
```

---

### 4.3 Eliminate props drilling

**Rule**  
Do not pass props through intermediate components that do not use them. Use the Composition pattern to let the top-level component own the data and render children directly.

**Reasoning**  
Props drilling creates implicit coupling between parent and all intermediary components. When a prop changes or is removed — say, a `recommendedItems` feature is dropped — every component in the chain must be updated, even those that merely forwarded the prop without using it.

**Recommended Pattern**  
Composition: remove shallow wrappers; assemble JSX close to state so only real consumers receive data. Use Context, slots, render props, etc. when you need to reach deep consumers without middle layers.

```typescript
// ❌ Avoid — ItemEditBody receives and forwards props it doesn't own
function ItemEditModal({ open, items, recommendedItems, onConfirm, onClose }) {
  const [keyword, setKeyword] = useState("");
  return (
    <Modal open={open} onClose={onClose}>
      <ItemEditBody
        keyword={keyword}
        onKeywordChange={setKeyword}
        items={items}
        recommendedItems={recommendedItems} // just passing through
        onConfirm={onConfirm}              // just passing through
        onClose={onClose}                  // just passing through
      />
    </Modal>
  );
}

function ItemEditBody({ keyword, onKeywordChange, items, recommendedItems, onConfirm, onClose }) {
  // uses keyword and onKeywordChange; everything else is forwarded again
  return (
    <>
      <Input value={keyword} onChange={(e) => onKeywordChange(e.target.value)} />
      <Button onClick={onClose}>Close</Button>
      <ItemEditList keyword={keyword} items={items} recommendedItems={recommendedItems} onConfirm={onConfirm} />
    </>
  );
}


// ✅ Prefer — Composition: ItemEditModal renders children directly, no intermediary
function ItemEditModal({ open, items, recommendedItems, onConfirm, onClose }) {
  const [keyword, setKeyword] = useState("");

  return (
    <Modal open={open} onClose={onClose}>
      <Input value={keyword} onChange={(e) => setKeyword(e.target.value)} />
      <Button onClick={onClose}>Close</Button>
      <ItemEditList
        keyword={keyword}
        items={items}
        recommendedItems={recommendedItems}
        onConfirm={onConfirm}
      />
    </Modal>
  );
}
// Removing recommendedItems now only requires changing ItemEditModal and ItemEditList — not ItemEditBody.
```

---

## Using all four principles together

Abstraction can raise cohesion but lower readability. Duplication can lower coupling but hurt cohesion if only one copy is updated. Prioritize for long-term ease of modification.
